## Implementation Plan

### Phase 1: Parse Skeleton & Skin Data from glTF

**File: `gltf_level.rs`**

The existing `parse_character_glb()` only extracts position/uv/normal. Extend it to also extract:

1. **Joint indices** (`JOINTS_0` accessor) — `[u16; 4]` per vertex
2. **Joint weights** (`WEIGHTS_0` accessor) — `[f32; 4]` per vertex
3. **Inverse bind matrices** — from the glTF `skin` object
4. **Joint hierarchy** — parent indices for each bone
5. **Animation tracks** — per-bone rotation/translation/scale keyframes from glTF `animations[]`

```rust
// New vertex struct replacing CharacterVertex
pub struct SkinnedVertex {
    pub pos: [f32; 3],
    pub uv: [f32; 2],
    pub nrm: [f32; 3],
    pub joints: [u32; 4],   // bone indices
    pub weights: [f32; 4],  // blend weights (sum to 1.0)
}

// Skeleton data
pub struct Skeleton {
    pub joint_count: usize,
    pub inverse_bind_matrices: Vec<Mat4>,  // one per joint
    pub parent_indices: Vec<Option<usize>>, // bone hierarchy
}

// Animation clip
pub struct AnimationClip {
    pub name: String,
    pub duration: f32,
    pub channels: Vec<AnimationChannel>,
}

pub struct AnimationChannel {
    pub joint_index: usize,
    pub property: AnimProperty, // Translation, Rotation, Scale
    pub times: Vec<f32>,
    pub values: Vec<[f32; 4]>, // quat for rotation, vec3+pad for trans/scale
}
```

**glTF parsing notes:**
- Access `skin.joints()` for the joint node list
- Access `skin.inverse_bind_matrices()` for the IBM accessor
- For each `mesh.primitive()`, read `JOINTS_0` (u8 or u16) and `WEIGHTS_0` (f32)
- Parse `document.animations()` for keyframe data
- The `gltf` crate (already in Cargo.toml v1.4.1) supports all of this

### Phase 2: GPU Bone Matrix Buffer

**File: `render.rs`**

Create a uniform/storage buffer for the bone matrices that the vertex shader will sample.

```rust
// Max 64 bones (Mixamo uses 33, leaves headroom)
const MAX_JOINTS: usize = 64;

// Per-frame bone matrices uploaded to GPU
// Each matrix = inverse_bind * joint_world_transform
pub struct BoneBuffer {
    pub buffer: wgpu::Buffer, // MAX_JOINTS * 64 bytes (Mat4)
    pub bind_group: wgpu::BindGroup,
}
```

Upload updated bone matrices every frame after computing animation pose.

### Phase 3: Vertex Skinning Shader

**File: `render.rs` (SHADER_CHAR_TEX replacement)**

Replace the current character shader with one that does linear blend skinning:

```wgsl
struct SkinnedVin {
    @location(0) pos: vec3<f32>,
    @location(1) uv: vec2<f32>,
    @location(2) norm: vec3<f32>,
    @location(3) joints: vec4<u32>,
    @location(4) weights: vec4<f32>,
};

@group(1) @binding(0) var<storage, read> bone_matrices: array<mat4x4<f32>>;

@vertex fn vs_skinned(v: SkinnedVin) -> Vout {
    // Linear blend skinning
    let skin_mat =
        bone_matrices[v.joints.x] * v.weights.x +
        bone_matrices[v.joints.y] * v.weights.y +
        bone_matrices[v.joints.z] * v.weights.z +
        bone_matrices[v.joints.w] * v.weights.w;

    let world_pos = (cu.model * skin_mat * vec4<f32>(v.pos, 1.0)).xyz;
    let world_n = normalize((cu.model * skin_mat * vec4<f32>(v.norm, 0.0)).xyz);

    var o: Vout;
    o.clip = cu.vp * vec4<f32>(world_pos, 1.0);
    o.uv = v.uv;
    o.world_n = world_n;
    o.world_pos = world_pos;
    return o;
}

// Fragment shader stays the same (cel-shading, neon spill, etc.)
```

### Phase 4: Animation Playback (CPU-side)

**New file: `client/src/animation.rs`**

Compute bone matrices each frame on CPU, upload to GPU buffer.

```rust
pub struct AnimationState {
    pub current_clip: usize,
    pub time: f32,
    pub speed: f32,
    pub looping: bool,
}

impl AnimationState {
    /// Sample all bone transforms at current time, compute final matrices
    pub fn compute_bone_matrices(
        &self,
        skeleton: &Skeleton,
        clips: &[AnimationClip],
    ) -> Vec<Mat4> {
        let clip = &clips[self.current_clip];
        let t = if self.looping {
            self.time % clip.duration
        } else {
            self.time.min(clip.duration)
        };

        // 1. Sample each channel at time t (lerp translation, slerp rotation)
        // 2. Build local transforms per joint
        // 3. Walk hierarchy: world_transform[i] = world_transform[parent] * local[i]
        // 4. Final matrix[i] = world_transform[i] * inverse_bind_matrices[i]
        // 5. Return vec of Mat4 to upload to GPU
    }
}
```

**Animation state machine** (integrate into `lib.rs` game loop):

```rust
// Map game state to animation clip
fn pick_animation(velocity: Vec3, is_shooting: bool, is_dead: bool) -> &str {
    if is_dead { return "walking_to_dying"; }
    if is_shooting { return "firing_rifle"; }
    let speed = velocity.length();
    if speed < 0.1 { return "rifle_aiming_idle"; }
    if speed > 5.0 { return "rifle_run"; }
    // Check direction relative to facing for strafe/backwards
    "walking"
}
```

### Phase 5: Wire Into Existing Systems

**File: `lib.rs`**

1. Load `yakuza_shooter.glb` via `include_bytes!()` or fetch
2. Parse skeleton + animations + skinned mesh using extended `parse_character_glb()`
3. Create `BoneBuffer` on GPU
4. Each frame:
   - Update `AnimationState` based on player/NPC movement
   - Call `compute_bone_matrices()`
   - Upload matrices to GPU buffer
   - Draw with skinned shader pipeline

**File: `render.rs`**

1. Add `SkinnedVertex` to vertex buffer layout (pos + uv + norm + joints + weights)
2. Create new render pipeline with skinned vertex shader
3. Add bone matrix storage buffer bind group
4. In `draw_world()`, render skinned character instead of billboard when 3D mode active

### CharacterSkin (no extra variant)

`Boss`, `Rival`, and `Remote` are **logical** roles only; all use the same `yakuza_shooter.glb` mesh when skinned. Optional second `CharacterDraw` (`character_rival`) is unused in the default app (`None`).

## Performance Notes

- 250k verts is high for WASM. Consider decimating to ~20k in Blender before export for production. The Blender file at `tokyo-theme/newchar1/character_shooter.blend` has the undecimated mesh — add a Decimate modifier (ratio ~0.08) and re-export.
- Bone matrix computation is cheap (33 bones × Mat4 multiply per frame)
- Storage buffer for bones is tiny (~2KB)
- The expensive part is the extra vertex attributes (joints + weights) increasing vertex buffer size

